t-size:12pt">may be ignored, e.g. in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">case for a social housing provider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in which case the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> saving would only be £212 from a bill of £515, so a 41% saving. For CfSH 6 there are diminishing returns as more of the electricity is exported during the day with nothing to consume it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The calculation makes many assumptions including:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CfSH and 2016 Part L fabric is identical, so the only benefit of CfSH is the solar PV</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is a solar PV solution even for CfSH 6 – large roof area, high efficiency panels required</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Electricity consumption, intraday distribution taken from EST “Powering the Nation” 2012 report</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Intraday consumption offset against real solar PV data, assumes smart import/export meter and not deemed export</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For both CfSH 5 &amp; 6 cases gas heating is used, if ASHP or GSHP were chosen then there would be additional benefit, particularly in the CfSH 6 as the HP could be used to reduce the exported electricity, so much of the hot water supply and some of the heating supply (winter) would be provided for free, so in this case the above estimates would be under-estimates</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A more detailed breakdown on a per house basis appears below:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:529.95pt"><tr style="height:15pt"><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:bottom; width:60.35pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:bottom; width:41pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td colspan="6" style="border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:1pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:210.55pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">CfSH 5</span></p></td><td colspan="6" style="border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:1pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:1pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:middle; width:218.05pt"><p style="margin:0p